posts.subject: Install Surf
posts.body:
If you're having trouble with shitty browsers that stutter, take ages to load, and consume all your RAM/CPU while browsing this javascript mess of a website, then I have the fix for you.
Install suckless browser, it'll use about 50MB shared and 10-20MB resident memory for every tab you have in this place.  It's a few lines of white man C around webpajeetGTK and has few dependencies. If you want tabs, you can install tabbed.
It does this by following what redditors call a "cargo cult," that is, it accepts programming virtues and follows them. How odd.

Gentoo's raiagent overlay has zeronet, and tor is part of the official repos.
They'll even run as their own users, allowing you to alow/disallow users by adding/removing them from groups, like white man unix is supposed to be.

>>721e022e-91a0-407d-a898-fcabf49ff027
TOR is supposed to have closed ports unless you're running a relay.
Open ports if you have a solution other than TOR for privacy and as such have it disabled.

>>26e2e99e-69cb-4b9d-ad0d-f09bb675d45f
Port 9051 is by default the tor control port. It's for tor programs to control tor.
If you want to make zeronet always use tor go to your configuration page and set tor always mode, and enable tor for tracker connections also. That way every zeronet connection will strictly be made through tor.

>>90f0973c-ca70-4600-842e-58e13e93eaf9
>>82e89b9a-4dde-4d1c-9cc0-8434b90e4fa4
I don't know what I'm doing either but from what I gather that limit is for the basic content of the website, that is, not even thumbnails, just the html and the like. It totals just 23MB and everyone has it downloaded anyway, so it doesn't really matter if we have one more seeder of that.
What you want to increase to really help is the optional files limit, that's the files people are attaching to their post and maybe more. You do that by clicking the zeronet symbol on the top right, clicking __FILES__ , and then clicking the arrow to the right of the "USED" meter. There you can edit the optional files limit.
I have set it to 10GB, I'm helping seed everything below 1MB, and the download is about 6GBs. That means I'm seeding the content that really matters, although only the stuff below 1MB. You can set it higher if you want, to seed bigger files people are attaching. If you hover your mouse over the orange number with a grey "OPTIONAL" written besides it on the 8chan section, you can see how much optional content exists on the website. Currently, that is about 33GBs.  Meanwhile, the older zeronet imageboard this one is based on has nearly 200GBs of content on it. 
So those are some ballpark estimates of how much storage you can currently dedicate and commit to the website.

I've been here for about half a week, and my zeronet daemon has maxed out my bandwidth seeding 100% of the time, so I think we're in need of seeders.

Dedicate it to freedumbs.
>zeronet daemon autoseeding 08chan
>i2p instance (make sure to set your bandwidth limit on i2pd)
>tor relay
I do that. There's also ipfs but I disabled it because I would use it but the damn thing eats all your bandwidth just being part of the DHT. It's not production-ready, so to speak.
If you have a good router, you can do QOS trickery and limit the bandwidth that laptop is allowed to use in such a way it can use everything unless another client in your network wants it, in which case you can tell it to use say 6.25% of what you got (the low priority qdisc on CAKE for instance). That way you're only really donating what you got to spare.

Install Devuan or a BSD (minus FreeBSD) on that laptop by the way, those are the operating systems that least require updates, and updating is still painful no matter what the operating system. They all require your overwatch, they all require a reboot eventually, and they all might fail if you don't "do it right". 
But If you use NetBSD for instance, the last supported release is 4 years old. Unless a package breaks, which they have a good historic of not doing, you can automate package updates for 4 years, and then manually jump in to upgrade your netbsd release.

posts.body:
>>7594158c-838d-4af9-b895-0620e061a5d5
In the zip, include a file titled "checksums.txt". Inside that file, include a checksum of every other file.
In the picture itself, put the hash sum of checksums.txt.
If someone tampers with the content hashes won't match, if the hash sum displayed in the picture is tampered with, we'll have multiple ones floating around and we know someone did something.

>>28692552-6ea4-454d-b24d-82d94e090cc6
Their cucked Dutch host was going to shut them down, they weren't legally allowed to even tell the public. But the gay furry who owns the website cooked up a plan to have it "conveniently" leak, so we had a 12 hour advance warning.
The shitstorm that ensued from people who suddenly found they might have to look at sickening 3D pornography in the future created a surge of donators and independent archivers, archiveteam not being one of them because it's been taken over by nu-/g/, and ultimately, the website moved hosts because an archive autist with deep pockets cozied up with the website owner. The exact details he won't release.
The end result is there are lots of newfags from 4um and reddit who now know the website, but on the flip side, the torrents are more well seeded.
He also talked about eventually shutting down e-hentai in 2020 and how he's tired of running the community for about 20 years,
but suddenly he doesn't mind continuing to run the website anymore, which makes me suspicious.

>>ba382f5d-104a-409f-b0dc-69b618937a42
Things are the same as they are before the temporary shutdown. Loli and all.
We did get a torrent containing everything tagged loli and shota on exhentai circulating at least.

>>184dc6b5-ceea-4f36-90b5-48fea5160a5f
>And then what do you do to make a second install?
You edit some scripts but there's not really a reason to make a second zeronet install anyway.
>And does that configure it to use the Tor daemon's auth_cookie?
You add the zeronet user to the tor group and make the auth_cookie group-readable.

>>adad6b54-35dd-4720-88c7-b12b3ea7ffe1
>I'm not blackpill
I doubt it.
The media is kvetching over us, if we weren't a threat they wouldn't be.
All we need is something like 08chan built on top of a privacy-focused network, and no, python+JS garbage like zeronet running over a glowinthedark deanonymization protocol like tor doesn't count. It's currently what we have, but doesn't even come close to solving the problem.
Once we do have something like that going, we can even celebrate that some didn't make it, because they certainly aren't the ones we'd want.
